  "prompt": "When people say \"Maths\" instead of \"Math\" are they indicating plurality in some way?",
  "response": "Yes, when people say \"maths\" instead of \"math,\" they are typically indicating plurality in a way. The term \"maths\" is commonly used in British English and is short for \"mathematics,\" which is a plural noun referring to the various branches of the discipline (like algebra, geometry, calculus, etc.). \n\nIn contrast, \"math\" is the term used in American English, where it is treated as a singular noun. Both terms refer to the same subject, but the difference in usage reflects variations between American and British English. So, in the case of \"maths,\" it does emphasize the idea of multiple aspects of the subject.",
